<subSubSection id="C307654D8722FFDD46C3A0B16666080A" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA236C68722FFDD46C3A0B164570BBA" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,609]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">
It is very difficult to recognize the species only with the description and redescription, without seeing a photograph of the 
<typeStatus id="54A688648722FFDD4722A09D648D0ABE" box="[294,392,187,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">holotype</typeStatus>
or 
<typeStatus id="54A688648722FFDD47AAA09D67140ABE" box="[430,529,187,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">paratype</typeStatus>
, especially because the general appearance is very similar to other species of the genus, as for example, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD47A4A0F967E40A92" authority="Bates, 1872" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1872" box="[416,737,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignobilis">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD47A4A0F967570A92" box="[416,594,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">Estola ignobilis</emphasis>
Bates, 1872
</taxonomicName>
(see photograph of a 
<typeStatus id="54A688648722FFDD45D8A0F961360A92" box="[988,1075,223,249]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">syntype</typeStatus>
on 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8C4B378722FFDD4264A0F961F00A92" author="Bezark, L. G." box="[1120,1269,223,249]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" refId="ref3374" refString="Bezark, L. G. (2022) A photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the World. New World Cerambycidae Catalog. Available from: http: // bezbycids. com / byciddb / wdefault. asp? w = n / (accessed 26 January 2022)" type="url" year="2022">Bezark 2022</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, seeing photographs of the 
<typeStatus id="54A688648722FFDD47BEA12567180B76" box="[442,541,259,285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">paratype</typeStatus>
, the general color and color of the pubescence do not agree well with those in the descriptions. Even the key provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8C4B378722FFDD4453A10166140B2A" author="Breuning, S." box="[599,785,295,321]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" pagination="1 - 210" refId="ref3490" refString="Breuning, S. (1974) Revision des Rhodopinini americains. Studia Entomologica, 17 (1 - 4), 1 - 210." type="journal article" year="1974">Breuning (1974)</bibRefCitation>
does not help because many features used in the couplets are questionable or even subjective. For example, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD44CEA16D664E0B0E" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1872" box="[714,843,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignobilis">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD44CEA16D664E0B0E" box="[714,843,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">E. ignobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD4586A16D66D60B0E" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1955" box="[898,979,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD4586A16D66D60B0E" box="[898,979,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">E. freyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were separated in the alternative of couplet “51” (translated): “Elytra densely dotted with very small, fairly distinct whitish spots,” leading to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD4309A14960860BE2" box="[1293,1411,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignobili">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD4309A14960860BE2" box="[1293,1411,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">E. ignobili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s / “Elytra without such spots,” leading to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD444BA1B567A50BC6" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1955" box="[591,672,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD444BA1B567A50BC6" box="[591,672,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">E. freyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The feature used is not easy to be recognized and, often, is variable intraspecifically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236C68722FFDD46C3A1FD6666080A" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,609]" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">
Fortunately, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD4750A1FD64D60B9E" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1955" box="[340,467,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD4750A1FD64D60B9E" box="[340,467,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">Estola freyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD4461A1FD67E00B9E" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1872" box="[613,741,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignobilis">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD4461A1FD67E00B9E" box="[613,741,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">E. ignobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and also from nearly all species of the genus, by the large size of the eyes. It can be easily recognized by the large upper eye lobes (
<figureCitation id="13262A438722FFDD459FA1D966EB0872" box="[923,1006,510,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–16. 12–15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1876,1900]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,946,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-317@5.[151,1436,946,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12–16. 12–15) Estola freyi Breuning, 1955, paratype: 12) Dorsal habitus; 13) Lateral habitus; 14) Labels; 15) Upper eye lobes. 16) Estola ignobilis Bates, 1872, female from Costa Rica, upper eye lobes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457472" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457472/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
), which are also moderately near each other (it is not a sexual feature in the genus). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD44B6A20566310856" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1872" box="[690,820,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignobilis">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD44B6A20566310856" box="[690,820,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">E. ignobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13262A438722FFDD4547A20566930855" box="[835,918,547,574]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–16. 12–15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1876,1900]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,946,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-317@5.[151,1436,946,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12–16. 12–15) Estola freyi Breuning, 1955, paratype: 12) Dorsal habitus; 13) Lateral habitus; 14) Labels; 15) Upper eye lobes. 16) Estola ignobilis Bates, 1872, female from Costa Rica, upper eye lobes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457472" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457472/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), the upper eye lobes are narrower and distant from each other. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458722FFDD4751A26164D0080A" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1955" box="[341,469,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48722FFDD4751A26164D0080A" box="[341,469,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="595">Estola freyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is illustrated for the first time here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
